irical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield: agentic table reasoning. Standard baselines ought to include TaPERA (ACL 2024), Chain-of-Table (ICLR 2024), Reflexion, ExpeL, LATS — none of these are in the main comparison tables. Backbone dependency is the load-bearing finding: Qwen3-1.7B + DTR collapses to 17.93 EM on Fact Checking vs DeepSeek-V3 + DTR at 58.22 — a ~3.2x gap from the same framework. The agentic mechanism does not rescue weaker backbones.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is accessible and the motivating example (hierarchical headers, long-horizon analytic queries) is intuitive for a non-expert. However, \"Deep Tabular Research\" as a task name is at risk of being read as a rebrand of multi-step Table QA (TaPERA, Chain-of-Table); positioning would benefit from explicit demarcation.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nagentic-ai\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (23 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no — github_repo_url is null and DTR-Bench release is not advertised in the abstract\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): partial — cites RealHitBench (2025), DeepSeek-V3, but omits Reflexion / ExpeL / LATS / TaPERA from main comparison tables despite their methodological closeness\n\n## Author assertion strength\nconfident — claims of \"novel task formalization\", \"principled framework\", \"superior foundation for deep tabular research\" are stated without hedging despite the modest marginal-ablation gains and backbone dependency.\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
